WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:00.580 --> 00:00:07.009
A bedroom at around 9pm. It’s quiet, save
for the rustle of the leaves in the garden

00:00:07.009 --> 00:00:14.070
outside. We’re side by side, each absorbed
in a different world. One of us might be in

00:00:14.070 --> 00:00:20.330
a submarine beneath the arctic ice floe, the
other is flitting through the salons of 18th-century

00:00:20.330 --> 00:00:27.699
Paris. Every so often our toes touch momentarily
but without raising notice. We might briefly

00:00:27.699 --> 00:00:33.820
stretch a hand to touch the nape of the partner’s
neck before turning a page. We can hear our

00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:41.680
partner very lightly breathing. There is – blessedly
– no need to say anything at all. And so

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:48.960
it goes, for what might be an hour or more.
It’s modest, comfortable and sweet. And

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:55.760
it is, of course, a pleasure that our society
is almost congenitally prone not to notice

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:02.210
or respect. When we’re invited to picture
what a relationship might be for, we imagine

00:01:02.210 --> 00:01:07.430
typically colourful scenarios: passionate
sex up against a wall, a celebration of a

00:01:07.430 --> 00:01:13.220
triumph at work, heading for the airport for
a mini-break, the mutual exploration of one

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:20.140
another’s souls. And yet when the true pleasures
of long-term love are assessed, a rather different

00:01:20.140 --> 00:01:25.890
set of images emerges, far less dramatic,
but also far more real and in their own way

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:31.720
gratifying: the knowing sideways smile our
partner gives us in the presence of a parent

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:37.730
who has been tricky in the past, watching
a TV drama episode by episode and bantering

00:01:37.730 --> 00:01:43.800
about the characters and plotlines, sitting
on the floor sorting the socks after the wash,

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:48.920
the chat we have after the friends who came
for lunch have departed, assembling a flat

00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:53.920
pack bookcase and realising we’ve both got
the instructions entirely wrong and that it’s

00:01:53.920 --> 00:01:55.920
almost rather funny.
